# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cofactor-biochemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/3-phosphoadenosine-5-phosphosulfate] APS and PAPS are intermediates in the reduction of sulfate to sulfite, an exothermic conversion that is carried out by sulfate-reducing bacteria.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/3-phosphoadenosine-5-phosphosulfate] In these organisms, sulfate serves as an electron acceptor, akin to the use of O2 as an electron acceptor by aerobic organisms.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/3-phosphoadenosine-5-phosphosulfate] Sulfate is not reduced directly but must be activated by the formation of APS or PAPS.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/3-phosphoadenosine-5-phosphosulfate] These carriers of activated sulfate are produced by reaction with ATP.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/3-phosphoadenosine-5-phosphosulfate] Reduction of APS leads to sulfite, which is further reduced to hydrogen sulfide, which is excreted.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/3-phosphoadenosine-5-phosphosulfate] This process is called dissimilatory sulfate reduction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/3-phosphoadenosine-5-phosphosulfate] Reduction of PAPS, a more elaborated sulfate ester, leads also to hydrogen sulfide.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/3-phosphoadenosine-5-phosphosulfate] But in this case, the product is used in biosynthesis, e.g. for the production of cysteine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/3-phosphoadenosine-5-phosphosulfate] The latter process is called assimilatory sulfate reduction because the sulfate sulfur is assimilated.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/5-10-methylenetetrahydrofolate] As an intermediate in one-carbon metabolism, 5,10-CH2-THF converts to 5-methyltetrahydrofolate, 5-formyltetrahydrofolate, and methenyltetrahydrofolate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/5-10-methylenetetrahydrofolate] It is substrate for the enzyme methylenetetrahydrofolate reductase (MTHFR), which gives 5-methyltetrahydrofolate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/5-10-methylenetetrahydrofolate] It is mainly produced by the reaction of tetrahydrofolate with serine, catalyzed by the enzyme serine hydroxymethyltransferase.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/5-10-methylenetetrahydrofolate] Methylenetetrahydrofolate is a source of the equivalent of formaldehyde or CH22+ in biosyntheses.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/5-10-methylenetetrahydrofolate] Methylenetetrahydrofolate is also an intermediate in the detoxification of formaldehyde.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/5-10-methylenetetrahydrofolate] It is the one-carbon donor for thymidylate synthase, for methylation of 2-deoxy-uridine-5-monophosphate (dUMP) to 2-deoxy-thymidine-5-monophosphate (dTMP).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/5-10-methylenetetrahydrofolate] The coenzyme is necessary for the biosynthesis of thymidine and is the C1-donor in the reactions catalyzed by TS and thymidylate synthase (FAD).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/5-10-methylenetetrahydrofolate] [6R]-5,10-methylene-THF is a biomodulator that has proven to enhance the desired cytotoxic antitumor effect of Fluorouracil (5-FU) and can bypass the metabolic pathway required by other folates (such as leucovorin) to achieve necessary activation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/5-10-methylenetetrahydrofolate] The active metabolite is being evaluated in clinical trials for patients with colorectal cancer in combination with 5-FU.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] In organic chemistry, an **acetyl group** is a functional group denoted by the chemical formula −COCH3 and the structure −C(=O)−CH3.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] It is sometimes represented by the symbol **Ac** (not to be confused with the element actinium).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] In IUPAC nomenclature, an acetyl group is called an **ethanoyl** **group**.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] An acetyl group contains a methyl group (−CH3) that is single-bonded to a carbonyl (C=O), making it an acyl group.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] The acetyl moiety is a component of many organic compounds, including acetic acid, the neurotransmitter acetylcholine, acetyl-CoA, acetylcysteine, acetaminophen (also known as paracetamol), and acetylsalicylic acid (also known as aspirin).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] Acetylation is the chemical reaction known as "ethanoylation" in the IUPAC nomenclature.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] It depicts a reactionary process that injects an acetyl functional group into a chemical compound.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] The opposite reaction is called "**de**acetylation", and this is the **removal** of the acetyl group.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] Enzymes which perform acetylation on proteins or other biomolecules are known as acetyltransferases.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] In biological organisms, acetyl groups are commonly transferred from acetyl-CoA to other organic molecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] Acetyl-CoA is an intermediate in the biological synthesis and in the breakdown of many organic molecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] Acetyl-CoA is also created during the second stage of cellular respiration (pyruvate decarboxylation) by the action of pyruvate dehydrogenase on pyruvic acid.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] Proteins are often modified via acetylation, for various purposes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] For example, acetylation of histones by histone acetyltransferases (HATs) results in an expansion of local chromatin structure, allowing transcription to occur by enabling RNA polymerase to access DNA.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] However, removal of the acetyl group by histone deacetylases (HDACs) condenses the local chromatin structure, thereby preventing transcription.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] Acetylation can be achieved by chemists using a variety of methods, most commonly with the use of acetic anhydride or acetyl chloride, often in the presence of a tertiary or aromatic amine base.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] The amine base is primarily used to capture free protons, but may also further activate the acetyl group towards nucleophilic attack.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] Acetylated organic molecules exhibit increased ability to cross the selectively permeable blood–brain barrier.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] Acetylation helps a given drug reach the brain more quickly, making the drug's effects more intense and increasing the effectiveness of a given dose.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] The acetyl group in acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin) enhances its effectiveness relative to the natural anti-inflammatant salicylic acid.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] In similar manner, acetylation converts the natural painkiller morphine into the far more potent heroin (diacetylmorphine).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] There is some evidence that acetyl-L-carnitine may be more effective for some applications than L-carnitine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] Acetylation of resveratrol holds promise as one of the first anti-radiation medicines for human populations.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] The term "acetyl" was coined by the German chemist Justus von Liebig in 1839 to describe what is now known as the vinyl group (coined in 1851).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acetyl] "Acetyl" is derived from the Latin *acētum,* meaning "vinegar.", and the Greek *Húlē,* meaning substance, or material.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In biology and biochemistry, the **active site** is the region of an enzyme where substrate molecules bind and undergo a chemical reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The active site consists of amino acid residues that form temporary bonds with the substrate, the *binding site*, and residues that catalyse a reaction of that substrate, the ***catalytic site***.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Although the active site occupies only ~10–20% of the volume of an enzyme, it is the most important part as it directly catalyzes the chemical reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It usually consists of three to four amino acids, while other amino acids within the protein are required to maintain the tertiary structure of the enzymes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Each active site is evolved to be optimised to bind a particular substrate and catalyse a particular reaction, resulting in high specificity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This specificity is determined by the arrangement of amino acids within the active site and the structure of the substrates.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Sometimes enzymes also need to bind with some cofactors to fulfil their function.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The active site is usually a groove or pocket of the enzyme which can be located in a deep tunnel within the enzyme, or between the interfaces of multimeric enzymes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] An active site can catalyse a reaction repeatedly as residues are not altered at the end of the reaction (they may change during the reaction, but are regenerated by the end).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This process is achieved by lowering the activation energy of the reaction, so more substrates have enough energy to undergo reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Usually, an enzyme molecule has only one active site, and the active site fits with one specific type of substrate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] An active site contains a binding site that binds the substrate and orients it for catalysis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The orientation of the substrate and the close proximity between it and the active site is so important that in some cases the enzyme can still function properly even though all other parts are mutated and lose function.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Initially, the interaction between the active site and the substrate is non-covalent and transient.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] There are four important types of interaction that hold the substrate in a defined orientation and form an enzyme-substrate complex (ES complex): hydrogen bonds, van der Waals interactions, hydrophobic interactions and electrostatic force interactions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The charge distribution on the substrate and active site must be complementary, which means all positive and negative charges must be cancelled out.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Otherwise, there will be a repulsive force pushing them apart.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The active site usually contains non-polar amino acids, although sometimes polar amino acids may also occur.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The binding of substrate to the binding site requires at least three contact points in order to achieve stereo-, regio-, and enantioselectivity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] For example, alcohol dehydrogenase which catalyses the transfer of a hydride ion from ethanol to NAD+ interacts with the substrate methyl group, hydroxyl group and the pro-*(R)* hydrogen that will be abstracted during the reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In order to exert their function, enzymes need to assume their correct protein fold (*native fold*) and tertiary structure.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] To maintain this defined three-dimensional structure, proteins rely on various types of interactions between their amino acid residues.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] If these interactions are interfered with, for example by extreme pH values, high temperature or high ion concentrations, this will cause the enzyme to denature and lose its catalytic activity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] A tighter fit between an active site and the substrate molecule is believed to increase the efficiency of a reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] If the tightness between the active site of DNA polymerase and its substrate is increased, the fidelity, which means the correct rate of DNA replication will also increase.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Most enzymes have deeply buried active sites, which can be accessed by a substrate via access channels.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] There are three proposed models of how enzymes fit their specific substrate: the lock and key model, the induced fit model, and the conformational selection model.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The latter two are not mutually exclusive: conformational selection can be followed by a change in the enzyme's shape.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Additionally, a protein may not wholly follow either model.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Amino acids at the binding site of ubiquitin generally follow the induced fit model, whereas the rest of the protein generally adheres to conformational selection.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Factors such as temperature likely influences the pathway taken during binding, with higher temperatures predicted to increase the importance of conformational selection and decrease that of induced fit.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This concept was suggested by the 19th-century chemist Emil Fischer.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] He proposed that the active site and substrate are two stable structures that fit perfectly without any further modification, just like a key fits into a lock.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] If one substrate perfectly binds to its active site, the interactions between them will be strongest, resulting in high catalytic efficiency.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] As time went by, limitations of this model started to appear.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] For example, the competitive enzyme inhibitor methylglucoside can bind tightly to the active site of 4-alpha-glucanotransferase and perfectly fits into it.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] However, 4-alpha-glucanotransferase is not active on methylglucoside and no glycosyl transfer occurs.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The Lock and Key hypothesis cannot explain this, as it would predict a high efficiency of methylglucoside glycosyl transfer due to its tight binding.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Apart from competitive inhibition, this theory cannot explain the mechanism of action of non-competitive inhibitors either, as they do not bind to the active site but nevertheless influence catalytic activity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Daniel Koshland's theory of enzyme-substrate binding is that the active site and the binding portion of the substrate are not exactly complementary.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The induced fit model is a development of the lock-and-key model and assumes that an active site is flexible and changes shape until the substrate is completely bound.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This model is similar to a person wearing a glove: the glove changes shape to fit the hand.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The enzyme initially has a conformation that attracts its substrate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Enzyme surface is flexible and only the correct catalyst can induce interaction leading to catalysis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Conformational changes may then occur as the substrate is bound.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] After the reaction products will move away from the enzyme and the active site returns to its initial shape.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This hypothesis is supported by the observation that the entire protein domain could move several nanometers during catalysis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This movement of protein surface can create microenvironments that favour the catalysis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This model suggests that enzymes exist in a variety of conformations, only some of which are capable of binding to a substrate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] When a substrate is bound to the protein, the equilibrium in the conformational ensemble shifts towards those able to bind ligands (as enzymes with bound substrates are removed from the equilibrium between the free conformations).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Positively charged sodium ion and negatively charged fluoride ion attract each other to form sodium fluoride under electrostatic interaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Hydrogen bond between two water molecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Van der Waals force between two acetone molecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The lower acetone molecule contains a partially negative oxygen atom that attracts partially positive carbon atom in the upper acetone.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Hydrophobic and hydrophilic groups tend to assemble with the same kind of molecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Once the substrate is bound and oriented to the active site, catalysis can begin.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The residues of the catalytic site are typically very close to the binding site, and some residues can have dual-roles in both binding and catalysis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] During enzyme catalytic reaction, the substrate and active site are brought together in a close proximity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Firstly, when substrates bind within the active site the effective concentration of it significantly increases than in solution.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This means the number of substrate molecules involved in the reaction is also increased.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This process also reduces the desolvation energy required for the reaction to occur.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In solution substrate molecules are surrounded by solvent molecules and energy is required for enzyme molecules to replace them and contact with the substrate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Since bulk molecules can be excluded from the active site this energy output can be minimised.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Next, the active site is designed to reorient the substrate to reduce the activation energy for the reaction to occur.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The alignment of the substrate, after binding, is locked in a high energy state and can proceed to the next step.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In addition, this binding is favoured by entropy as the energy cost associated with solution reaction is largely eliminated since solvent cannot enter active site.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In the end, the active site may manipulate the Molecular orbital of the substrate into a suitable orientation to reduce activation energy.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The electrostatic states of substrate and active site must be complementary to each other.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] A polarized negatively charged amino acid side chain will repel uncharged substrate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] But if the transition state involves the formation of an ion centre then the side chain will now produce a favourable interaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Many enzymes including serine protease, cysteine protease, protein kinase and phosphatase evolved to form transient covalent bonds between them and their substrates to lower the activation energy and allow the reaction to occur.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This process can be divided into 2 steps: formation and breakdown.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The former step is rate-limit step while the later step is needed to regenerate intact enzyme.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Metal ions have multiple roles during the reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Firstly it can bind to negatively charged substrate groups so they will not repel electron pairs from active site's nucleophilic groups.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It can attract negatively charged electrons to increase electrophilicity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It can also bridge between active site and substrate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] At last, they may change the conformational structure of the substrate to favour reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In some reactions, protons and hydroxide may directly act as acid and base in term of specific acid and specific base catalysis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] But more often groups in substrate and active site act as Brønsted–Lowry acid and base.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This is called general acid and general base theory.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The easiest way to distinguish between them is to check whether the reaction rate is determined by the concentrations of the general acid and base.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] If the answer is yes then the reaction is the general type.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Since most enzymes have an optimum pH of 6 to 7, the amino acids in the side chain usually have a p*K*a of 4~10.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Candidate include aspartate, glutamate, histidine, cysteine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] These acids and bases can stabilise the nucleophile or electrophile formed during the catalysis by providing positive and negative charges.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Quantitative studies of enzymatic reactions often found that the acceleration of chemical reaction speed cannot be fully explained by existing theories like the approximation, acid/base catalysis and electrophile/nucleophile catalysis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] And there is an obvious paradox: in reversible enzymatic reaction if the active site perfectly fits the substrates then the backward reaction will be slowed since products cannot fit perfectly into the active site.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] So conformational distortion was introduced and argues that both active site and substrate can undergo conformational changes to fit with each other all the time.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This theory is a little similar to the Lock and Key Theory, but at this time the active site is preprogrammed to bind perfectly to substrate in transition state rather than in ground state.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The formation of transition state within the solution requires a large amount of energy to relocate solvent molecules and the reaction is slowed.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] So the active site can substitute solvent molecules and surround the substrates to minimize the counterproductive effect imposed by the solution.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The presence of charged groups with the active site will attract substrates and ensure electrostatic complementarity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In reality, most enzyme mechanisms involve a combination of several different types of catalysis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The role of glutathione(GSH) is to remove accumulated reactive oxygen species which may damage cells.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] During this process, its thiol side chain is oxidised and two glutathione molecules are connected by a disulphide bond to form a dimer(GSSG).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In order to regenerate glutathione the disulphide bond has to be broken, In human cells, this is done by glutathione reductase(GR).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Glutathione reductase is a dimer that contains two identical subunits.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It requires one NADP and one FAD as the cofactors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The active site is located in the linkage between two subunits.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The NADPH is involved in the generation of FADH-.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In the active site, there are two cysteine residues besides the FAD cofactor and are used to break the disulphide bond during the catalytic reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] NADPH is bound by three positively charged residues: Arg-218, His-219 and Arg-224.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The catalytic process starts when the FAD is reduced by NADPH to accept one electron and from FADH−.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It then attacks the disulphide bond formed between 2 cysteine residues, forming one SH bond and a single S− group.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This S− group will act as a nucleophile to attack the disulphide bond in the oxidised glutathione(GSSG), breaking it and forming a cysteine-SG complex.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The first SG− anion is released and then receives one proton from adjacent SH group and from the first glutathione monomer.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Next the adjacent S− group attack disulphide bond in cysteine-SG complex and release the second SG− anion.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It receives one proton in solution and forms the second glutathione monomer.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Chymotrypsin is a serine endopeptidase that is present in pancreatic juice and helps the hydrolysis of proteins and peptide.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It catalyzes the hydrolysis of peptide bonds in L-isomers of tyrosine, phenylalanine, and tryptophan.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In the active site of this enzyme, three amino acid residues work together to form a catalytic triad which makes up the catalytic site.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In chymotrypsin, these residues are Ser-195, His-57 and Asp-102.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The mechanism of chymotrypsin can be divided into two phases.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] First, Ser-195 nucleophilically attacks the peptide bond carbon in the substrate to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The nucleophilicity of Ser-195 is enhanced by His-57, which abstracts a proton from Ser-195 and is in turn stabilised by the negatively charged carboxylate group (RCOO−) in Asp-102.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Furthermore, the tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate generated in this step is stabilised by hydrogen bonds from Ser-195 and Gly-193.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In the second stage, the R'NH group is protonated by His-57 to form R'NH2 and leaves the intermediate, leaving behind the acylated Ser-195.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] His-57 then acts as a base again to abstract one proton from a water molecule.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The resulting hydroxide anion nucleophilically attacks the acyl-enzyme complex to form a second tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate, which is once again stabilised by H bonds.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In the end, Ser-195 leaves the tetrahedral intermediate, breaking the CO bond that connected the enzyme to the peptide substrate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] A proton is transferred to Ser-195 through His-57, so that all three amino acid return to their initial state.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Substrate unbinding is influenced by various factors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Larger ligands generally stay in the active site longer, as do those with more rotatable bonds (although this may be a side effect of size).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] When the solvent is excluded from the active site, less flexible proteins result in longer residence times.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] More hydrogen bonds shielded from the solvent also decrease unbinding.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Enzymes can use cofactors as 'helper molecules'.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Coenzymes are referred to those non-protein molecules that bind with enzymes to help them fulfill their jobs.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Mostly they are connected to the active site by non-covalent bonds such as hydrogen bond or hydrophobic interaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] But sometimes a covalent bond can also form between them.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] For example, the heme in cytochrome C is bound to the protein through thioester bond.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In some occasions, coenzymes can leave enzymes after the reaction is finished.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Otherwise, they permanently bind to the enzyme.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Coenzyme is a broad concept which includes metal ions, various vitamins and ATP.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] If an enzyme needs coenzyme to work itself, it is called an apoenzyme.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] In fact, it alone cannot catalyze reactions properly.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Only when its cofactor comes in and binds to the active site to form holoenzyme does it work properly.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It contains a distinct conjugated isoalloxazine ring system.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Flavin has multiple redox states and can be used in processes that involve the transfer of one or two electrons.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It can act as an electron acceptor in reaction, like the oxidation of NAD to NADH, to accept two electrons and form 1,5-dihydroflavin.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] On the other hand, it can form semiquinone(free radical) by accepting one electron, and then converts to fully reduced form by the addition of an extra electron.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This property allows it to be used in one electron oxidation process.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Inhibitors disrupt the interaction between enzyme and substrate, slowing down the rate of a reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] There are different types of inhibitor, including both reversible and irreversible forms.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Competitive inhibitors are inhibitors that only target free enzyme molecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] They compete with substrates for free enzyme acceptor and can be overcome by increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Competitive inhibitors usually have structural similarities to the substrates and or ES complex.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] As a result, they can fit into the active site and trigger favourable interactions to fill in the space and block substrates from entry.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] They can also induce transient conformational changes in the active site so substrates cannot fit perfectly with it.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] After a short period of time, competitive inhibitors will drop off and leave the enzyme intact.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Inhibitors are classified as non-competitive inhibitors when they bind both free enzyme and ES complex.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Since they do not compete with substrates for the active site, they cannot be overcome by simply increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] They usually bind to a different site on the enzyme and alter the 3-dimensional structure of the active site to block substrates from entry or leaving the enzyme.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Irreversible inhibitors are similar to competitive inhibitors as they both bind to the active site.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] However, irreversible inhibitors form irreversible covalent bonds with the amino acid residues in the active site and never leave.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Therefore, the active site is occupied and the substrate cannot enter.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Occasionally the inhibitor will leave but the catalytic site is permanently altered in shape.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] These inhibitors usually contain electrophilic groups like halogen substitutes and epoxides.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] As time goes by more and more enzymes are bound by irreversible inhibitors and cannot function anymore.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] HIV protease inhibitors are used to treat patients having AIDS virus by preventing its DNA replication.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] HIV protease is used by the virus to cleave Gag-Pol polyprotein into 3 smaller proteins that are responsible for virion assembly, package and maturation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This enzyme targets the specific phenylalanine-proline cleave site within the target protein.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] If HIV protease is switched off the virion particle will lose function and cannot infect patients.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Since it is essential in viral replication and is absent in healthy human, it is an ideal target for drug development.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] HIV protease belongs to aspartic protease family and has a similar mechanism.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Firstly the aspartate residue activates a water molecule and turns it into a nucleophile.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Then it attacks the carbonyl group within the peptide bond (NH-CO) to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The nitrogen atom within the intermediate receives a proton, forming an amide group and subsequent rearrangement leads to the breakdown of the bond between it and the intermediate and forms two products.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Inhibitors usually contain a nonhydrolyzable hydroxyethylene or hydroxyethylamine groups that mimic the tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Since they share a similar structure and electrostatic arrangement to the transition state of substrates they can still fit into the active site but cannot be broken down, so hydrolysis cannot occur.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Strychnine is a neurotoxin that causes death by affecting nerves that control muscular contraction and cause respiration difficulty.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The impulse is transmitted between the synapse through a neurotransmitter called acetylcholine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It is released into the synapse between nerve cells and binds to receptors in the postsynaptic cell.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Then an action potential is generated and transmitted through the postsynaptic cell to start a new cycle.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Glycine can inhibit the activity of neurotransmitter receptors, thus a larger amount of acetylcholinesterase is required to trigger an action potential.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This makes sure that the generation of nerve impulses is tightly controlled.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] However, this control is broken down when strychnine is added.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It inhibits glycine receptors(a chloride channel) and a much lower level of neurotransmitter concentration can trigger an action potential.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Nerves now constantly transmit signals and cause excessive muscular contraction, leading to asphyxiation and death.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Diisopropyl fluorophosphate (DIFP) is an irreversible inhibitor that blocks the action of serine protease.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] When it binds to the enzyme a nucleophilic substitution reaction occurs and releases one hydrogen fluoride molecule.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The OH group in the active site acts as a nucleophile to attack the phosphorus in DIFP and form a tetrahedral intermediate and release a proton.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Then the P-F bond is broken, one electron is transferred to the F atom and it leaves the intermediate as F− anion.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] It combines with a proton in solution to form one HF molecule.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] A covalent bond formed between the active site and DIFP, so the serine side chain is no longer available to the substrate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Identification of active sites is crucial in the process of drug discovery.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] The 3-D structure of the enzyme is analysed to identify active site residues and design drugs which can fit into them.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Proteolytic enzymes are targets for some drugs, such as protease inhibitors, which include drugs against AIDS and hypertension.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] These protease inhibitors bind to an enzyme's active site and block interaction with natural substrates.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] An important factor in drug design is the strength of binding between the active site and an enzyme inhibitor.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] If the enzyme found in bacteria is significantly different from the human enzyme then an inhibitor can be designed against that particular bacterium without harming the human enzyme.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] If one kind of enzyme is only present in one kind of organism, its inhibitor can be used to specifically wipe them out.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Active sites can be mapped to aid the design of new drugs such as enzyme inhibitors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This involves the description of the size of an active site and the number and properties of sub-sites, such as details of the binding interaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Modern database technology called CPASS (Comparison of Protein Active Site Structures) however allows the comparison of active sites in more detail and the finding of structural similarity using software.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] An allosteric site is a site on an enzyme, unrelated to its active site, which can bind an effector molecule.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] This interaction is another mechanism of enzyme regulation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Allosteric modification usually happens in proteins with more than one subunit.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] Allosteric interactions are often present in metabolic pathways and are beneficial in that they allow one step of a reaction to regulate another step.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/active-site] They allow an enzyme to have a range of molecular interactions, other than the highly specific active site.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] In chemistry, an **acyl group** is a moiety derived by the removal of one or more hydroxyl groups from an oxoacid, including inorganic acids.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] It contains a double-bonded oxygen atom and an organyl group (R−C=O) or hydrogen in the case of formyl group (H−C=O).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] In organic chemistry, the acyl group (IUPAC name **alkanoyl** if the organyl group is alkyl) is usually derived from a carboxylic acid, in which case it has the formula R−C(=O)−, where R represents an organyl group or hydrogen.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Although the term is almost always applied to organic compounds, acyl groups can in principle be derived from other types of acids such as sulfonic acids and phosphonic acids.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] In the most common arrangement, acyl groups are attached to a larger molecular fragment, in which case the carbon and oxygen atoms are linked by a double bond.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] There are five main types of acyl derivatives.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acid halides are the most reactive towards nucleophiles, followed by anhydrides, esters, and amides.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Carboxylate ions are essentially unreactive towards nucleophilic substitution, since they possess no leaving group.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The reactivity of these five classes of compounds covers a broad range; the relative reaction rates of acid chlorides and amides differ by a factor of 1013.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] A major factor in determining the reactivity of acyl derivatives is leaving group ability, which is related to acidity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Weak bases are better leaving groups than strong bases; a species with a strong conjugate acid (e.g. hydrochloric acid) will be a better leaving group than a species with a weak conjugate acid (e.g. acetic acid).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Thus, chloride ion is a better leaving group than acetate ion.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The reactivity of acyl compounds towards nucleophiles decreases as the basicity of the leaving group increases, as the table shows.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Another factor that plays a role in determining the reactivity of acyl compounds is resonance.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Amides exhibit two main resonance forms.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Both are major contributors to the overall structure, so much so that the amide bond between the carbonyl carbon and the amide nitrogen has significant double bond character.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The energy barrier for rotation about an amide bond is 75–85 kJ/mol (18–20 kcal/mol), much larger than values observed for normal single bonds.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] For example, the C–C bond in ethane has an energy barrier of only 12 kJ/mol (3 kcal/mol).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Once a nucleophile attacks and a tetrahedral intermediate is formed, the energetically favorable resonance effect is lost.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] This helps explain why amides are one of the least reactive acyl derivatives.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Esters exhibit less resonance stabilization than amides, so the formation of a tetrahedral intermediate and subsequent loss of resonance is not as energetically unfavorable.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Anhydrides experience even weaker resonance stabilization, since the resonance is split between two carbonyl groups, and are more reactive than esters and amides.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] In acid halides, there is very little resonance, so the energetic penalty for forming a tetrahedral intermediate is small.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] This helps explain why acid halides are the most reactive acyl derivatives.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Well-known acyl compounds are the acyl chlorides, such as acetyl chloride (CH3COCl) and benzoyl chloride (C6H5COCl).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] These compounds, which are treated as sources of acylium cations, are good reagents for attaching acyl groups to various substrates.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Amides (**RC(O)**NR′2) and esters (**RC(O)**OR′) are classes of acyl compounds, as are ketones (**RC(O)**R′) and aldehydes (**RC(O)**H), where R and R′ stand for organyl (or hydrogen in the case of formyl).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acylium ions are cations of the formula RCO+.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The carbon–oxygen bond length in these cations is near 1.1 Å (110-112 pm), which is shorter than the 112.8 pm of carbon monoxide and indicates triple-bond character.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The carbon centres of acylium ions generally have a linear geometry and sp atomic hybridization, and are best represented by a resonance structure bearing a formal positive charge on the oxygen (rather than carbon): [R−C≡O+].
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] They are characteristic fragments observed in EI-mass spectra of ketones.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acylium ions are common reactive intermediates, for example in the Friedel–Crafts acylation and many other organic reactions such as the Hayashi rearrangement.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acyl radicals are commonly generated when thiyl or other, more electrophilic radicals abstract hydrogen atoms from aldehydes (alkyl radicals do so very inefficiently).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acyl anions are almost always unstable—usually too unstable to be exploited synthetically.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] They readily react with the neutral aldehyde to form an acyloin dimer.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Hence, synthetic chemists have developed various acyl anion synthetic equivalents, such as dithianes, as surrogates.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] However, as a partial exception, hindered dialkylformamides (e.g., diisopropylformamide, HCON*i*Pr2) can undergo deprotonation at low temperature (−78 °C) with lithium diisopropylamide as the base to form a carbamoyl anion stable at these temperatures.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] In biochemistry there are many instances of acyl groups, in all major categories of biochemical molecules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acyl-CoAs are acyl derivatives formed via fatty acid metabolism.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acetyl-CoA, the most common derivative, serves as an acyl donor in many biosynthetic transformations.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Names of acyl groups of amino acids are formed by replacing the *-ine* suffix with *-yl*.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] For example, the acyl group of glycine is glycyl, and of lysine is lysyl.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Names of acyl groups of ribonucleoside monophosphates such as AMP (5′-adenylic acid), GMP (5′-guanylic acid), CMP (5′-cytidylic acid), and UMP (5′-uridylic acid) are adenylyl, guanylyl, cytidylyl, and uridylyl respectively.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] In phospholipids, the acyl group of phosphatidic acid is called phosphatidyl-.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acyl ligands are intermediates in many carbonylation reactions, which are important in some catalytic reactions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Metal acyls arise usually via insertion of carbon monoxide into metal–alkyl bonds.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Metal acyls also arise from reactions involving acyl chlorides with low-valence metal complexes or by the reaction of organolithium compounds with metal carbonyls.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Metal acyls are often described by two resonance structures, one of which emphasizes the basicity of the oxygen center.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] *O*-alkylation of metal acyls gives Fischer carbene complexes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The common names of acyl groups are derived typically by replacing the **-ic acid** suffix of the corresponding carboxylic acid's common name with **-yl** (or **-oyl**), as shown in the table below.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The acyls are between the hydrocarbyls and the carboxylic acids.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The hydrocarbyl group names that end in -yl are not acyl groups, but alkyl groups derived from alkanes (methyl, ethyl, propyl, butyl), alkenyl groups derived from alkenes (propenyl, butenyl), or aryl groups (benzyl).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acyl compounds react with nucleophiles via an addition mechanism: the nucleophile attacks the carbonyl carbon, forming a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] This reaction can be accelerated by acidic conditions, which make the carbonyl more electrophilic, or basic conditions, which provide a more anionic and therefore more reactive nucleophile.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The tetrahedral intermediate itself can be an alcohol or alkoxide, depending on the pH of the reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The tetrahedral intermediate of an acyl compound contains a substituent attached to the central carbon that can act as a leaving group.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] After the tetrahedral intermediate forms, it collapses, recreating the carbonyl C=O bond and ejecting the leaving group in an elimination reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] As a result of this two-step addition/elimination process, the nucleophile takes the place of the leaving group on the carbonyl compound by way of an intermediate state that does not contain a carbonyl.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Both steps are reversible and as a result, nucleophilic acyl substitution reactions are equilibrium processes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Because the equilibrium will favor the product containing the best nucleophile, the leaving group must be a comparatively poor nucleophile in order for a reaction to be practical.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Under acidic conditions, the carbonyl group of the acyl compound **1** is protonated, which activates it towards nucleophilic attack.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] In the second step, the protonated carbonyl **2** is attacked by a nucleophile (H−Z) to give tetrahedral intermediate **3**.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Proton transfer from the nucleophile (Z) to the leaving group (X) gives **4**, which then collapses to eject the protonated leaving group (H−X), giving protonated carbonyl compound **5**.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The loss of a proton gives the substitution product, **6**.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Because the last step involves the loss of a proton, nucleophilic acyl substitution reactions are considered catalytic in acid.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Also note that under acidic conditions, a nucleophile will typically exist in its protonated form (i.e.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Under basic conditions, a nucleophile (Nuc) attacks the carbonyl group of the acyl compound **1** to give tetrahedral alkoxide intermediate **2**.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] The intermediate collapses and expels the leaving group (X) to give the substitution product **3**.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] While nucleophilic acyl substitution reactions can be base-catalyzed, the reaction will not occur if the leaving group is a stronger base than the nucleophile (i.e. the leaving group must have a lower p*K*a than the nucleophile).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Unlike acid-catalyzed processes, both the nucleophile and the leaving group exist as anions under basic conditions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] This mechanism is supported by isotope labeling experiments.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] When ethyl propionate with an oxygen-18-labeled ethoxy group is treated with sodium hydroxide (NaOH), the oxygen-18 label is completely absent from propionic acid and is found exclusively in the ethanol.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] In **acyloxy** groups the acyl group is bonded to oxygen: R−C(=O)−O−R′ where R−C(=O) is the acyl group.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] Acylium ions are cations of the formula R−C≡O+.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/acyl] They are intermediates in Friedel-Crafts acylations.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] In individuals with supraventricular tachycardia (SVT), adenosine is a first line treatment used to help identify and convert the rhythm.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Certain SVTs can be successfully terminated with adenosine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] This includes any re-entrant arrhythmias that require the AV node for the re-entry, e.g., AV reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) and AV nodal reentrant tachycardia (AVNRT).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] In addition, atrial tachycardia can sometimes be terminated with adenosine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Fast rhythms of the heart that are confined to the atria (e.g., atrial fibrillation and atrial flutter) or ventricles (e.g., monomorphic ventricular tachycardia), and do not involve the AV node as part of the re-entrant circuit, are not typically converted by adenosine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] However, the ventricular response rate is temporarily slowed with adenosine in such cases.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Because of the effects of adenosine on AV node-dependent SVTs, adenosine is considered a class V antiarrhythmic agent.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] When adenosine is used to cardiovert an abnormal rhythm, it is normal for the heart to enter ventricular asystole for a few seconds.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] This can be disconcerting to a normally conscious patient, and is associated with angina-like sensations in the chest.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine is used as an adjunct to thallium (Tl-201) or technetium (Tc-99m) myocardial perfusion scintigraphy (nuclear stress test) in patients unable to undergo adequate stress testing with exercise.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] When used to treat SVT, adenosine is administered intravenously as a rapid bolus (typically 0.10–0.15 mg/kg initially) over 1-2 seconds, followed by a rapid saline flush (often using a 2-way or 3-way stopcock).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] If the initial dose is ineffective, it may be repeated every 2 minutes with a slightly increased dose (0.05–0.1 mg/kg increments) every 2 minutes up to a maximum total dose of 0.3 mg/kg (not exceeding 12 mg).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] When given to dilate the arteries, such as in a "stress test", the dosage is typically 0.14 mg/kg/min, administered for 4 or 6 minutes, depending on the protocol.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] The recommended dose may be increased in patients on theophylline since methylxanthines prevent binding of adenosine at receptor sites.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] The dose is often decreased in patients on dipyridamole (Persantine) and diazepam (Valium) because adenosine potentiates the effects of these drugs.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] The recommended dose is also reduced by half in patients presenting congestive heart failure, myocardial infarction, shock, hypoxia, and/or chronic liver disease or chronic kidney disease, and in elderly patients.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adverse effects associated with adenosine administration are primarily due to its activation of adenosine receptors on vascular tissue, resulting in vasodilation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Side effects of adenosine include skin flushing, lightheadedness, nausea, sweating, nervousness, numbness, and a sense of impending doom.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] These effects are typically very short-lived due to adenosine's rapid metabolism and short half-life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Less common, but more serious, cardiovascular effects can occur, such as cardiac arrhythmias (including premature atrial and ventricular contractions and atrioventricular (AV) block), hypotension, cardiac ischemia, and prolonged asystole.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Dipyridamole potentiates the action of adenosine, requiring the use of lower doses.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Methylxanthines (e.g. caffeine found in coffee, theophylline found in tea, or theobromine found in chocolate) have a purine structure and bind to some of the same receptors as adenosine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Methylxanthines act as competitive antagonists of adenosine and can blunt its pharmacological effects.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Individuals taking large quantities of methylxanthines may require increased doses of adenosine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Caffeine acts by blocking binding of adenosine to the adenosine A1 receptor, which enhances release of the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Caffeine also increases cyclic AMP levels through nonselective inhibition of phosphodiesterase.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] "Caffeine has a three-dimensional structure similar to that of adenosine," which allows it to bind and block its receptors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Alcohol can increase extracellular adenosine levels.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine is an endogenous purine nucleoside that modulates many physiological processes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Cellular signaling by adenosine occurs through four known adenosine receptor subtypes (A1, A2A, A2B, and A3).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Extracellular adenosine concentrations from normal cells are approximately 300 nM; however, in response to cellular damage (e.g., in inflammatory or ischemic tissue), these concentrations are quickly elevated (600–1,200 nM).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Thus, in regard to stress or injury, the function of adenosine is primarily that of cytoprotection preventing tissue damage during instances of hypoxia, ischemia, and seizure activity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Activation of A2A receptors produces a constellation of responses that in general can be classified as anti-inflammatory.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Enzymatic production of adenosine can be anti-inflammatory or immunosuppressive.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] All adenosine receptor subtypes (A1, A2A, A2B, and A3) are G-protein-coupled receptors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] The four receptor subtypes are further classified based on their ability to either stimulate or inhibit adenylate cyclase activity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] The A1 receptors couple to Gi/o and decrease cAMP levels, while the A2 adenosine receptors couple to Gs, which stimulates adenylate cyclase activity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] In addition, A1 receptors couple to Go, which has been reported to mediate adenosine inhibition of Ca2+ conductance, whereas A2B and A3 receptors also couple to Gq and stimulate phospholipase activity.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Researchers at Cornell University have recently shown adenosine receptors to be key in opening the blood-brain barrier (BBB).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Mice dosed with adenosine have shown increased transport across the BBB of amyloid plaque antibodies and prodrugs associated with Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's, multiple sclerosis, and cancers of the central nervous system.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine is an endogenous agonist of the ghrelin/growth hormone secretagogue receptor.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] However, while it is able to increase appetite, unlike other agonists of this receptor, adenosine is unable to induce the secretion of growth hormone and increase its plasma levels.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] When it is administered intravenously, adenosine causes transient heart block in the atrioventricular (AV) node.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] This is mediated via the A1 receptor, inhibiting adenylyl cyclase, reducing cAMP and so causing cell hyperpolarization by increasing K+ efflux via inward rectifier K+ channels, subsequently inhibiting Ca2+ current.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] It also causes endothelial-dependent relaxation of smooth muscle as is found inside the artery walls.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] This causes dilation of the "normal" segments of arteries, i.e. where the endothelium is not separated from the tunica media by atherosclerotic plaque.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] This feature allows physicians to use adenosine to test for blockages in the coronary arteries, by exaggerating the difference between the normal and abnormal segments.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] The administration of adenosine also reduces blood flow to coronary arteries past the occlusion.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Other coronary arteries dilate when adenosine is administered while the segment past the occlusion is already maximally dilated, which is a process called coronary steal.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] This leads to less blood reaching the ischemic tissue, which in turn produces the characteristic chest pain.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine used as a second messenger can be the result of *de novo* purine biosynthesis via adenosine monophosphate (AMP), though it is possible other pathways exist.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] When adenosine enters the circulation, it is broken down by adenosine deaminase, which is present in red blood cells and the vessel wall.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Dipyridamole, an inhibitor of adenosine nucleoside transporter, allows adenosine to accumulate in the blood stream.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] This causes an increase in coronary vasodilatation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine deaminase deficiency is a known cause of immunodeficiency.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] The adenosine analog NITD008 has been reported to directly inhibit the recombinant RNA-dependent RNA polymerase of the dengue virus by terminating its RNA chain synthesis.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] This interaction suppresses peak viremia and rise in cytokines and prevents lethality in infected animals, raising the possibility of a new treatment for this flavivirus.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] The 7-deaza-adenosine analog has been shown to inhibit the replication of the hepatitis C virus.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] BCX4430 is protective against Ebola and Marburg viruses.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Such adenosine analogs are potentially clinically useful since they can be taken orally.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine is believed to be an anti-inflammatory agent at the A2A receptor.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Topical treatment of adenosine to foot wounds in diabetes mellitus has been shown in lab animals to drastically increase tissue repair and reconstruction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Topical administration of adenosine for use in wound-healing deficiencies and diabetes mellitus in humans is currently under clinical investigation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Methotrexate's anti-inflammatory effect may be due to its stimulation of adenosine release.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] In general, adenosine has an inhibitory effect in the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Caffeine's stimulatory effects are credited primarily (although not entirely) to its capacity to block adenosine receptors, thereby reducing the inhibitory tonus of adenosine in the CNS.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] This reduction in adenosine activity leads to increased activity of the neurotransmitters dopamine and glutamate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Experimental evidence suggests that adenosine and adenosine agonists can activate Trk receptor phosphorylation through a mechanism that requires the adenosine A2A receptor.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine in the brain acts through three major receptor subtypes—A1, A2A, and A3—distributed across various neuronal and glial populations.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Activation of neuronal A1 receptors generally exerts inhibitory effects, contributing to synaptic regulation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine has been shown to promote thickening of hair on people with thinning hair.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine is a key factor in regulating the body's sleep-wake cycle.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Adenosine levels build up in the brain during periods of wakefulness, causing a need to sleep when levels become too high, and lowers during periods of sleep, giving a sensation of restedness when waking.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Higher adenosine levels correlate with a stronger feeling of sleepiness, also known as sleep drive or sleep pressure.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] Cognitive behavioral therapy for insomnia (CBT-I), which is considered one of the most effective treatments for insomnia, utilizes short-term sleep deprivation to raise and regulate adenosine levels in the body, for the intended promotion of consistent and sustained sleep in the long term.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] A principal component of cannabis delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinol (THC) and the endocannabinoid anandamide (AEA) induces sleep in rats by increasing adenosine levels in the basal forebrain.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] These components also significantly increase slow-wave sleep during the sleep cycle, mediated by CB1 receptor activation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] These findings identify a potential therapeutic use of cannabinoids to induce sleep in conditions where sleep may be severely attenuated.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/adenosine] It also plays a role in regulation of blood flow to various organs through vasodilation.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] A **cofactor** is a non-protein chemical compound or metallic ion that is required for an enzyme's role as a catalyst.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors can be considered "helper molecules" that assist in biochemical transformations.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The rates at which these happen are characterized in an area of study called enzyme kinetics.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors typically differ from ligands in that they often derive their function by remaining bound.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors can be classified into two types: inorganic ions and complex organic molecules called coenzymes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Coenzymes are mainly derived from vitamins and other organic essential nutrients in small amounts (some definitions limit the use of the term "cofactor" for inorganic substances; both types are included here).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Coenzymes are further divided into two types.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The first is called a "prosthetic group", which consists of a coenzyme that is tightly (or even covalently and, therefore, permanently) bound to a protein.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The second type of coenzymes are called "cosubstrates", and are transiently bound to the protein.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Cosubstrates may be released from a protein at some point, and then rebind later.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Both prosthetic groups and cosubstrates have the same function, which is to facilitate the reaction of enzymes and proteins.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] An inactive enzyme without the cofactor is called an apoenzyme, while the complete enzyme with cofactor is called a holoenzyme.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Some enzymes or enzyme complexes require several cofactors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors are often vitamins or made from vitamins.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Many contain the nucleotide adenosine monophosphate (AMP) as part of their structures, such as ATP, coenzyme A, FAD, and NAD+.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This common structure may reflect a common evolutionary origin as part of ribozymes in an ancient RNA world.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] It has been suggested that the AMP part of the molecule can be considered to be a kind of "handle" by which the enzyme can "grasp" the coenzyme to switch it between different catalytic centers.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Cofactors can be divided into two major groups: **organic** **cofactors**, such as flavin or heme; and **inorganic cofactors**, such as the metal ions Mg2+, Zn2+, Cu+, Mn2+ and iron–sulfur clusters.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors are sometimes further divided into *coenzymes* and *prosthetic groups*.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The term coenzyme refers specifically to enzymes and, as such, to the functional properties of a protein.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] On the other hand, "prosthetic group" emphasizes the nature of the binding of a cofactor to a protein (tight or covalent) and, thus, refers to a structural property.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Different sources give slightly different definitions of coenzymes, cofactors, and prosthetic groups.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Some consider tightly bound organic molecules as prosthetic groups and not as coenzymes, while others define all non-protein organic molecules needed for enzyme activity as coenzymes, and classify those that are tightly bound as coenzyme prosthetic groups.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] A 1980 letter in *Trends in Biochemistry Sciences* noted the confusion in the literature and the essentially arbitrary distinction made between prosthetic groups and coenzymes group and proposed the following scheme.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Here, cofactors were defined as an additional substance apart from protein and substrate that is required for enzyme activity and a prosthetic group as a substance that undergoes its whole catalytic cycle attached to a single enzyme molecule.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] However, the author could not arrive at a single all-encompassing definition of a "coenzyme" and proposed that this term be dropped from use in the literature.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The study of these cofactors falls under the area of bioinorganic chemistry.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] In nutrition, the list of essential trace elements reflects their role as cofactors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] In humans this list commonly includes iron, magnesium, manganese, cobalt, copper, zinc, and molybdenum.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Although chromium deficiency causes impaired glucose tolerance, no human enzyme that uses this metal as a cofactor has been identified.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Iodine is also an essential trace element, but this element is used as part of the structure of thyroid hormones rather than as an enzyme cofactor.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Calcium is, therefore, a cell signaling ion, and not usually considered a cofactor of the enzymes it regulates.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] In many cases, the cofactor includes both an inorganic and organic component.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] One diverse set of examples is the heme proteins, which consist of a porphyrin ring coordinated to iron.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Iron–sulfur clusters are complexes of iron and sulfur atoms held within proteins by cysteinyl residues.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] They play both structural and functional roles, including electron transfer, redox sensing, and as structural modules.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors are small organic molecules (typically a molecular mass less than 1000 Da) that can be either loosely or tightly bound to the enzyme and directly participate in the reaction.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] In the latter case, when it is difficult to remove without denaturing the enzyme, it can be called a prosthetic group.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] There is no sharp division between loosely and tightly bound cofactors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Many such as NAD+ can be tightly bound in some enzymes, while it is loosely bound in others.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Another example is thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP), which is tightly bound in transketolase or pyruvate decarboxylase, while it is less tightly bound in pyruvate dehydrogenase.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Other coenzymes, flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), biotin, and lipoamide, for instance, are tightly bound.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Tightly bound cofactors are, in general, regenerated during the same reaction cycle, while loosely bound cofactors can be regenerated in a subsequent reaction catalyzed by a different enzyme.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] In the latter case, the cofactor can also be considered a substrate or cosubstrate.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Vitamins can serve as precursors to many organic cofactors (e.g., vitamins B1, B2, B6, B12, niacin, folic acid) or as coenzymes themselves (e.g., vitamin C).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] However, vitamins do have other functions in the body.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Many organic cofactors also contain a nucleotide, such as the electron carriers NAD and FAD, and coenzyme A, which carries acyl groups.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Most of these cofactors are found in a huge variety of species, and some are universal to all forms of life.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] An exception to this wide distribution is a group of unique cofactors that evolved in methanogens, which are restricted to this group of archaea.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Although enzyme catalyzed industrial processes are highly efficient, some of the enzymes are dependent on nicotinamide cofactors (NADH/NAD+, NADP/NAPH).
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Due to the high price of such cofactors, these processes would not be economically competitive.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Recently, some synthetic organic compounds were identified as economically promising biomimetic counterparts of natural cofactors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Metabolism involves a vast array of chemical reactions, but most fall under a few basic types of reactions that involve the transfer of functional groups.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This common chemistry allows cells to use a small set of metabolic intermediates to carry chemical groups between different reactions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] These group-transfer intermediates are the loosely bound organic cofactors, often called coenzymes.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Each class of group-transfer reaction is carried out by a particular cofactor, which is the substrate for a set of enzymes that produce it, and a set of enzymes that consume it.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] An example of this are the dehydrogenases that use nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) as a cofactor.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Here, hundreds of separate types of enzymes remove electrons from their substrates and reduce NAD+ to NADH.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This reduced cofactor is then a substrate for any of the reductases in the cell that require electrons to reduce their substrates.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Therefore, these cofactors are continuously recycled as part of metabolism.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] As an example, the total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mole.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This ATP is constantly being broken down into ADP, and then converted back into ATP.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The energy used by human cells requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 moles of ATP daily, which is around 50 to 75 kg.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] In typical situations, humans use up their body weight of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This means that each ATP molecule is recycled 1000 to 1500 times daily.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors, such as ATP and NADH, are present in all known forms of life and form a core part of metabolism.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Such universal conservation indicates that these molecules evolved very early in the development of living things.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] At least some of the current set of cofactors may, therefore, have been present in the last universal ancestor, which lived about 4 billion years ago.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Organic cofactors may have been present even earlier in the history of life on Earth.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The nucleotide adenosine is a cofactor for many basic metabolic enzymes such as transferases.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Adenosine-based cofactors may have acted as adaptors that allowed enzymes and ribozymes to bind new cofactors through small modifications in existing adenosine-binding domains, which had originally evolved to bind a different cofactor.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This process of adapting a pre-evolved structure for a novel use is known as *exaptation*.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The first organic cofactor to be discovered was NAD+, which was identified by Arthur Harden and William Young 1906.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] They noticed that adding boiled and filtered yeast extract greatly accelerated alcoholic fermentation in unboiled yeast extracts.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] They called the unidentified factor responsible for this effect a *coferment*.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Through a long and difficult purification from yeast extracts, this heat-stable factor was identified as a nucleotide sugar phosphate by Hans von Euler-Chelpin.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Other cofactors were identified throughout the early 20th century, with ATP being isolated in 1929 by Karl Lohmann, and coenzyme A being discovered in 1945 by Fritz Albert Lipmann.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The functions of these molecules were at first mysterious, but, in 1936, Otto Heinrich Warburg identified the function of NAD+ in hydride transfer.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This discovery was followed in the early 1940s by the work of Herman Kalckar, who established the link between the oxidation of sugars and the generation of ATP.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This confirmed the central role of ATP in energy transfer that had been proposed by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Later, in 1949, Morris Friedkin and Albert L.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Lehninger proved that NAD+ linked metabolic pathways such as the citric acid cycle and the synthesis of ATP.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] In a number of enzymes, the moiety that acts as a cofactor is formed by post-translational modification of a part of the protein sequence.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This often replaces the need for an external binding factor, such as a metal ion, for protein function.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Potential modifications could be oxidation of aromatic residues, binding between residues, cleavage or ring-forming.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] These alterations are distinct from other post-translation protein modifications, such as phosphorylation, methylation, or glycosylation in that the amino acids typically acquire new functions.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] This increases the functionality of the protein; unmodified amino acids are typically limited to acid-base reactions, and the alteration of resides can give the protein electrophilic sites or the ability to stabilize free radicals.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Examples of cofactor production include tryptophan tryptophylquinone (TTQ), derived from two tryptophan side chains, and 4-methylidene-imidazole-5-one (MIO), derived from an Ala-Ser-Gly motif.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Characterization of protein-derived cofactors is conducted using X-ray crystallography and mass spectroscopy; structural data is necessary because sequencing does not readily identify the altered sites.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] The term is used in other areas of biology to refer more broadly to non-protein (or even protein) molecules that either activate, inhibit, or are required for the protein to function.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] For example, ligands such as hormones that bind to and activate receptor proteins are termed cofactors or coactivators, whereas molecules that inhibit receptor proteins are termed corepressors.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] One such example is the G protein-coupled receptor family of receptors, which are frequently found in sensory neurons.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] Ligand binding to the receptors activates the G protein, which then activates an enzyme to activate the effector.
[src:cofactor-biochemistry/cofactor-biochemistry] In order to avoid confusion, it has been suggested that such proteins that have ligand-binding mediated activation or repression be referred to as coregulators.
